Title: ''The Foundling'' by Charlotte Brontë
Name: Brontë, Charlotte, author
Notes: ''The foundling'': a tale written at the age of seventeen by Charlotte Brontë; 1833. Autograph fair copy with revisions and deletions, written in minute characters in imitation of print on both sides of nine octavo leaves of white laid paper. No watermark. The leaves have been bound by Charlotte to form one gathering of ten (10 is a stub) in brown sugar-paper wrappers. The title-page (f. 1) is signed ''Charlotte Brontë'', and bears the note ''This Book was begun May 31st 1833 and finished June the 27th 1833''. The Preface (f. 1b), attributed to Captain Tree, the pseudonymous author of the tale, is in Charlotte''s normal hand. At the foot of f. 2 is the note ''begun May 31st 1833'', while the end of the tale (f. 9b) is signed and dated ''Charlotte Brontë/Haworth June 27th - 1833''. The tale includes the following verses: burlesque verses, beginning ''Eaniala is a gurt bellaring bull'', f. 2b; ''The Swiss Emigrant''s Return'' (first printed, by Wise, in The Swiss Emigrant''s Return and Other Poems, 1917), 5b; ''Seranade'' (sic) (first printed in The Swiss Emigrant''s Return), ff. 5b-6; ''O wind that o''er the ocean'' (first published in The Complete Poems of Charlotte Brontë, 1923, as ''Destiny''), ff. 6b-7; ''Sound a lament in the halls of his father'' (first printed in The Swiss Emigrant''s Return as ''A Lament''), ff. 8b-9. The whole tale was first published in The Shakespeare Head Brontë, Miscellaneous and Unpublished Writings of Charlotte and P. B. Brontë, i, pp. 220-295. Ashley Library Catalogue, i, p. 70 (facsimile of ff. 1 and 7). Octavo; ff. ii+9. Tales: Charlotte Brontë, author: ''The Foundling'': a tale by Charlotte Brontë: 1833: Autogr. fair copy

Title: GEORGE SMITH MEMORIAL BEQUEST. Vols. I-III. The autograph fair copy of ''Jane Eyre'' by Charlotte Bronte
Name: Brontë, Charlotte, author
Notes: The autograph fair copy written out 16- 19 March 1847 (see vol. 1, f. i, and vol. I I I, f. 265) and sent to Messrs Smith, Elder and Co. on 24 Aug. 1847. First published, in 3 vols, on 16 Oct. 1847 as Jane Eyre. An Autobiography. Edited by Currer Bell. The manuscript was originally written as one volume, the folios being numbered consecutively throughout, viz. 1-255 (= vol. 1), 255 (lower half of page)-503 (= vol. II), and 504-768 (= vol. III),and the chapters being similarly treated (vol. II opens with the original chap. 16, vol. III with chap. 27). That the manuscript is a copy is shown by errors of transcription (see, e.g, vol. 1, ff. 69, 83, 222; vol. II, f. 76; vol. III, ff. 2, 113, 254). Verbal alterations or expansions of phrase, reflecting second thoughts, are few, but do occur (see, e.g, vol. 1, ff. 70, 139, 225, 228; vol. II, ff. 1, 8; vol. III, ff. 43, 60, 96, 97, 122); a few (e.g, vol. II, f. 31) are in pencil. The signatures and first leaf numbers of the gatherings of the printed text are usually indicated in the MS. (as also the compositors'' names), but in vol. I they do not agree after f. 193 with the printed text; in vols. II and III several are wanting. Paper. Three volumes. Quarto. A.D. 1847. The MS. is referred to in T. J. Wise, A Bibliography ... of the Brontë Family, 1917, p. 19, as being in the possession of Mrs Yates Thompson (daughter of George Smith) and the first page of the MS. is reproduced as the frontispiece

Title: GEORGE SMITH MEMORIAL BEQUEST. Vols. IV-VI. The autograph fair copy of 'Shirley', by Charlotte Brontë
Name: Brontë, Charlotte, author
Notes: The autographfair copy transcribed in 1848 (the last leaf of Vol. iv, f. 284, is dated Sept. 1848) and sent to the printers. First published, in 3 vols, on 26 Oct. 1849 as Shirley. A Tale. By Currer Bell, Author of 'Jane Eyre'. The manuscript was originally written as one volume, the pages being numbered consecutively throughout, viz. 1-284 (= Vol. IV), 285-573 (= vol. V), and 574-891 (= vol. VI), and the chapters being similarly treated (vol. V opens with the original chap. ii, vol. VI with chap. 23). Verbal alterations (and deletions) are more numerous than in the manuscript of 'Jane Eyre' (see, e.g, vol. IV, ff. 7, 18, 35, 38, 54, 83, 100; V, ff. 5, 7, 12, 80, 211; Vol. VI, ff. 1, 7, 22, 66, 171. In vol. IV the second paragraph (in chap. 1) was redrafted; the Sykes family was given originally the name of Roakes (see ff. 27, 28, 78, 97, 109, 147) and in one place (f. 31) the original name has remained unaltered at its second appearance on the page and thus appears in the printed text (P. 31). Moreover, chap. 4 (f. 59) was wrongly numbered chap. 3, an error repeated by the printer, though the number ofthe next chapter appears correctly in both the MS. (f. 76) and the printed text as 5. Other alterations in vol. iv are the substitution of 'Canadian' for 'American' (f.201) and of' 'Cliffbridge' for 'Scarbro'(f.267). A leaf is missing between ff. 214 and 216; the blank leaf substituted was in its present position when the manuscript was received in the British Museum. In vol. VI the original title of chap. 4 (= MS. chap. 26) was 'Le Cheval dompt@', which became in the printed text, 'The First Blue-Stocking', and that of chap. 9 (= MS. chap. 30) was 'Martin Yorke meets a Wood-Nymph', altered in the MS. to that adopted in the printed text, viz. 'The School-boy and the Woodnymph'. A footnote reference on f. 203, 'See Preface', shows that a preface was at one time projected. Signatures and first-leaf numbers of the gatherings of the printed text are usually indicated in the manuscript, as also the compositors' names, but there are several omissions. Paper. Three volumes. Quarto. A.D. 1848. The MS. is referred to in T. J. Wise, A Bibliography ... of the Bronti Family, 1917, P. 29, as being in the possession of Miss Ethel Murray Smith (daughter of George Smith)

Title: GEORGE SMITH MEMORIAL BEQUEST. Vols. VII-IX. The autograph fair copy of 'Villette' by Charlotte Brontë
Name: Brontë, Charlotte, author
Notes: The autograph fair copy transcribed in 1852, vol. VII, f. 1 being dated 29 Mar. 1852, and sent to the printers. First published, in 3 vols, On 28 Jan. 1853 as Villette. By Currer Bell, Author of 'Jane Eyre', 'Shirley', etc. The manuscript, like those of the two preceding novels, was originally in one volume, the folios being numbered consecutively throughout, viz. 1-272 (=vol. VII), 273-546 (=vol. VIII), and 546 (lower portion of page)-847 (=vol. IX), and the chapters being similarly treated (vol. VIII opens with the original chap. 17 and vol. IX with chap. 30). Many pages have been mutilated, and a memorandum on the flyleaf (f. 1), dated 22 Dec. 1896, notes those in vol. VII and records the fact that the original f. 216 was missing at that date. Verbal alterations (some in pencil, e.g, vol. VIII, f. 237) are numerous and several chapter-titles were altered: thus, in vol. VIII the original title of chap. 17, 'La Terrasse', was replaced by 'Auld Langsyne' and transferred to chap. 18, the original title of which, 'The Second Evening', is deleted; this may be connected with the fact that the first printed volume was presumably intended to end with chap. 17 (see f. 24, ad fin.). In vol. IX 'Fraternity', in pencil, is substituted for 'Fraternal Covenant' at the head of chap. 37. Chap. 38 is entitled 'Malign Aspect' ('Apple of Discord' in the printed edition). A number of titles throughout have been added in pencil (e.g. vol. VIII, chaps. 25, 26, 27). Chap. 41 has no title at all. As elsewhere in these MSS. the signatures and first-leaf numbers of the gatherings of the printed text are (with some omissions) indicated throughout. In vol. IX, ff. 609 (lower portion), the whole of 610-616, and upper part of 617 (by original foliation) are missing, but the text runs on as in the printed version; in the same volume a portion of the original f. 633 has been misplaced between ff. 770 and 771 (see printed text pp. go-gi). The character Lucy Snowe was originally named Lucy Frost (see, e.g, vol.VII, f. 48; vol. VIII, f. 21). Paper. Three volumes. Quarto. A.D. 1852. The MS. is referred to in T. J. Wise, A Bibliography ... of the Bronte Family, 1917, p. 33, as in the possession of Mrs Reginald Smith (daughter-in-law of George Smith)

The autographs, etc, were mounted in the album by Millar. One volume with two numbers. The collection was given two numbers as it was originally proposed to rebind and split the album, but this decision was later reversed. Title: MISCELLANEOUS LETTERS and papers; 16th cent.-1864. A Exhortation from R[ichard], Archbishop of Canterbury, to the Cistercian order, to pay tithes of their lands to the clergy; [1179]. Lat . (See Hist. Littéraire, vol. xiv, p. 618). Copy, 16th cent. f. 1 b. On the outer pages (ff. 1, 2 b) are recipes, in Latin, for making ink, and some questions of Canon Law, etc . B. Portion of an inventory of plate and jewels, apparently belonging to Henry VIII. f. 3. Included are spoons engraved with the arms of Thomas Cromwell, Earl of Essex (f. 4 b), and ' Prince Edwardes face graven in agathe sett in golde ' (f. 6); and on f. 5 b is a note that certain parcels were taken away by the king in person on 1st Sund. in Lent, a o 36 [1545]. C [Ulick Burke, Marquis of] Clanricarde, to the Marquis of Ormonde, Lord Lieut. of Ireland; Lexleape, 29 Mar. 1646. Autogr . transcript. Printed, except the last paragraph, in Carte's Ormonde, 1736, iii. p. 453. f. 7. D. Pedro Serrano, servant to Bernardino de Mendoza, Spanish Ambassador in England, to Anna de Mendoza, the ambassador's sister, giving an account of the trial and execution of Edmund Campion a.d other Jesuits; London, 4 Dec. 1581. With a postscript by the ambassador. Span . Contemp. copy . f. 9. From the Farnborough Fund. E. 1. S[amuel] F[oart] Simmons, M.D, to Baron [Amédée Emmanuel] de Haller, at Berne, relative to the disposal of the library of the latter's father, Albert de Haller; London, 14 May, 1778, Fr. f. 11. 2. - Du Roveray, print-dealer, to George Baker, stating terms for the sale of drawings by Stothard, Mortimer, Burney, W. Hamilton, and Westall; Bishopsgate, 22 Jan. 1806. f. 13. F. 1. Ferdinand, Archduke of Austria, to his commanders at Trieste, Gradisca and Marano, as to the movements of Spanish troops guarding the Venetian frontiers; Augsburg, 2 Dec. 1525. Germ. Signed. f. 15. 2. Instructions from the Emperor Rudolph II. to John, Baron von Khevenhueller, his ambassador to Spain; Prague, 8 Feb. 1593. Lat. Signed; with seal. f. 17. From the Farnborough Fund. G. 1. Two pages of Thomas de Quincey's ' Daughter of Lebanon (see Edinb. ed. 1856, p. 281). Autograph. f. 26. 2. Letter from C[harlotte] Brontë to James Hogg, sen, refusing to sanction the publication of her portrait; London, 13 June, 1850. f. 28. 3. Mark Lemon to James Hogg, jun, on the seriousness of life, and the good done by his ' old friend Mr. Punch ' : 25 Dec. 1863. f. 30. 4. John Leech to the same, on his inability to illustrate ' A Lady in search of a horse '; Brighton, 3 Jan. 1864. f. 33. From the Farnborough Fund. Paper; ff. 35. Folio

Title: MISCELLANEOUS original letters, etc.:-. A. Letters of Charles II. (a) to an unnamed nobleman, hoping to find in him ' a principle instrument ' towards bis restoration, and assuring him of reward; Paris, 10 Mar. 1654. f. 1;-(b) to ' Mr Rumball ' William Rumbold, thanking him for his constancy and desiring him to do his utmost to procure contributions for his support;. Cologne, 4 June, 1655. f. 3. Holograph. From the Farnborough Fund. B. 1. ''Air composé expressément pour le début de Duprez dans ''les Huguenots,'' par Meyerbeer, qui lui a envoyé, écrite de sa main, I''ébauche ci-incluse. - Cet air inedit a été chanté 10 fois par Duprez - en 1837 - et supprimé comme inutile.'' The above description is signed ''Gilbert Duprez'', for whom it was written in 1837. The music was written for insertion in Act v of the Opera, as an alternative to the original setting of the scene beginning ''Il I''aura! oui. Courons aux armes,'' following the air ''A la lueur de leurs torches,'' as published in 1836. The melody only of the first part of the air is given, but the second portion of it has the pianoforte part written under it, in score, followed by a neat copy of the same. ff. 6-9. 2. ''Amen'': Canon for 4 voices, in score, by Thomas Attwood. A shortened version of the same is given, also in the composer''s hand, in Add MS 35026, f. 16, of which the probable date is 1837. f. 11. From the Farnborough Fund. C. 1. Fragment of the first act of the second part of 'Faust,' by Johann Wolfgang von Goethe; circ. 1830? . Autograph. On a single paper leaf. It contains the four stanzas of the first chorus, 'Wenn sich lau die Lüfte füllen,' and the song of Ariel which follows, ending ' Trifft es euch so seyd ihr taub.' The only complete variation from the text of G. von Loeper (Berlin, 1870) is the stage-direction preceding Ariel''s song, '(Die Sonne geht auf). Faust erwacht.' for '(Ungeheures Getöse verkündet das Herannahen der Sonne).' There are a few corrections; one in the last line of the chorus is made upon a slip pasted down, a habit of the poet, as asserted by Johann Peter Eckermann, author of the Gespräche mit Goethe, in a letter dated Weimar, 14 July, 1853, attached by seal to the above. f. 12. 2. Letter from ' Currer Bell ' Charlotte Brontë to W. S. Williams, the publisher''s reader responsible for the acceptance of ' Jane Eyre,' with remarks on the life of a governess, on Carlyle''s style, etc; 15 June, 1848. f. 14. Paper; ff. 15. Folio
